# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ball-screw
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In mechanical engineering, **backlash**, sometimes called **lash**, **play**, or **slop**, is a clearance or lost motion in a mechanism caused by gaps between the parts.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] It can be defined as "the maximum distance or angle through which any part of a mechanical system may be moved in one direction without applying appreciable force or motion to the next part in mechanical sequence."p.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] 1-8 An example, in the context of gears and gear trains, is the amount of clearance between mated gear teeth.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] It can be seen when the direction of movement is reversed and the slack or lost motion is taken up before the reversal of motion is complete.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] It can be heard from the railway couplings when a train reverses direction.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Another example is in a valve train with mechanical tappets, where a certain range of lash is necessary for the valves to work properly.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Depending on the application, backlash may or may not be desirable.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Some amount of backlash is unavoidable in nearly all reversing mechanical couplings, although its effects can be negated or compensated for.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In many applications, the theoretical ideal would be zero backlash, but in actual practice some backlash must be allowed to prevent jamming.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Reasons for specifying a requirement for backlash include allowing for lubrication, manufacturing errors, deflection under load, and thermal expansion.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] A principal cause of undesired backlash is wear.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Factors affecting the amount of backlash required in a gear train include errors in profile, pitch, tooth thickness, helix angle and center distance, and run-out.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The greater the accuracy the smaller the backlash needed.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Backlash is most commonly created by cutting the teeth deeper into the gears than the ideal depth.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Another way of introducing backlash is by increasing the center distances between the gears.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Backlash, measured on the pitch circle, due to operating center modifications is defined by: The speed of the machine.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Standard practice is to make allowance for half the backlash in the tooth thickness of each gear.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] However, if the pinion (the smaller of the two gears) is significantly smaller than the gear it is meshing with then it is common practice to account for all of the backlash in the larger gear.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] This maintains as much strength as possible in the pinion's teeth.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The amount of additional material removed when making the gears depends on the pressure angle of the teeth.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] For a 14.5° pressure angle the extra distance the cutting tool is moved in equals the amount of backlash desired.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] For a 20° pressure angle the distance equals 0.73 times the amount of backlash desired.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] As a rule of thumb the average backlash is defined as 0.04 divided by the diametral pitch; the minimum being 0.03 divided by the diametral pitch and the maximum 0.05 divided by the diametral pitch.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In a gear train, backlash is cumulative.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] When a gear-train is reversed the driving gear is turned a short distance, equal to the total of all the backlashes, before the final driven gear begins to rotate.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] At low power outputs, backlash results in inaccurate calculation from the small errors introduced at each change of direction; at large power outputs backlash sends shocks through the whole system and can damage teeth and other components.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In certain applications, backlash is an undesirable characteristic and should be minimized.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The best example here is an analog radio tuner dial where one may make precise tuning movements both forwards and backwards.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] One of the more common designs splits the gear into two gears, each half the thickness of the original.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] One half of the gear is fixed to its shaft while the other half of the gear is allowed to turn on the shaft, but pre-loaded in rotation by small coil springs that rotate the free gear relative to the fixed gear.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In this way, the spring compression rotates the free gear until all of the backlash in the system has been taken out; the teeth of the fixed gear press against one side of the teeth of the pinion while the teeth of the free gear press against the other side of the teeth on the pinion.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Loads smaller than the force of the springs do not compress the springs and with no gaps between the teeth to be taken up, backlash is eliminated.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Another area where backlash matters is in leadscrews.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Again, as with the gear train example, the culprit is lost motion when reversing a mechanism that is supposed to transmit motion accurately.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Instead of gear teeth, the context is screw threads.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The linear sliding axes (machine slides) of machine tools are an example application.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Most machine slides for many decades, and many even today, have been simple (but accurate) cast-iron linear bearing surfaces, such as a dovetail- or box-slide, with an Acme leadscrew drive.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] With just a simple nut, some backlash is inevitable.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The next-more complex method than the simple nut is a split nut, whose halves can be adjusted, and locked with screws, so that the two sides ride, respectively, against leftward thread and the other side rides rightward faces.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Notice the analogy here with the radio dial example using split gears, where the split halves are pushed in opposing directions.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Unlike in the radio dial example, the spring tension idea is not useful here, because machine tools taking a cut put too much force against the screw.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Any spring light enough to allow slide movement at all would allow cutter chatter at best and slide movement at worst.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] These screw-adjusted split-nut-on-an-Acme-leadscrew designs cannot eliminate *all* backlash on a machine slide unless they are adjusted so tight that the travel starts to bind.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The axis can move in either direction without the go-past-and-come-back motion.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] This programmatic "backlash compensation" is a cheap solution, but professional grade CNCs use the more expensive backlash-eliminating drives mentioned above.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] This allows them to do 3D contouring with a ball-nosed endmill, for example, where the endmill travels around in many directions with constant rigidity and without delays.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In mechanical computers a more complex solution is required, namely a frontlash gearbox.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] This works by turning slightly faster when the direction is reversed to 'use up' the backlash slack.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Some motion controllers include backlash compensation.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Compensation may be achieved by simply adding extra compensating motion (as described earlier) or by sensing the load's position in a closed loop control scheme.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The dynamic response of backlash itself, essentially a delay, makes the position loop less stable and thus more prone to oscillation.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Backlash variation is defined as the difference between the maximum and minimum backlash occurring in a whole revolution of the larger of a pair of mating gears.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] Backlash in gear couplings allows for slight angular misalignment.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] There can be significant backlash in unsynchronized transmissions because of the intentional gap between the dogs in dog clutches.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] The gap is necessary to engage dogs when input shaft (engine) speed and output shaft (driveshaft) speed are imperfectly synchronized.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] If there was a smaller clearance, it would be nearly impossible to engage the gears because the dogs would interfere with each other in most configurations.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] In synchronized transmissions, synchromesh solves this problem.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] However, backlash is undesirable in precision positioning applications such as machine tool tables.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] It can be minimized by choosing ball screws or leadscrews with preloaded nuts, and mounting them in preloaded bearings.
[src:ball-screw/backlash-engineering] A preloaded bearing uses a spring and/or a second bearing to provide a compressive axial force that maintains bearing surfaces in contact despite reversal of the load direction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] A **ball bearing** is a type of rolling-element bearing that uses balls to maintain the separation between the bearing races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The purpose of a ball bearing is to reduce rotational friction and support radial and axial loads.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] It achieves this by using at least two races to contain the balls and transmit the loads through the balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In most applications, one race is stationary and the other is attached to the rotating assembly (e.g., a hub or shaft).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] As one of the bearing races rotates it causes the balls to rotate as well.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Because the balls are rolling, they have a much lower coefficient of friction than if two flat surfaces were sliding against each other.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Ball bearings tend to have lower load capacity for their size than other kinds of rolling-element bearings due to the smaller contact area between the balls and races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] However, they can tolerate some misalignment of the inner and outer races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Common ball bearing designs include *angular contact, axial, deep-groove,* and *preloaded pairs.* The balls in ball bearings can also be configured in various ways.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Ball bearings are used in a wide range of applications, some of which include skateboards and centrifugal pumps.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Although bearings had been developed since ancient times, the first modern recorded patent on ball bearings was awarded to Philip Vaughan, a Welsh inventor and ironmaster who created the first design for a ball bearing in Carmarthen in 1794.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] His is the first modern ball-bearing design, with the ball running along a groove in the axle assembly.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Jules Suriray, a Parisian bicycle mechanic, designed the first radial style ball bearing in 1869, which was then fitted to the winning bicycle ridden by James Moore in the world's first bicycle road race, Paris-Rouen, in November 1869.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] There are several common designs of ball bearing, each offering various performance trade-offs.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] They can be made from many different materials, including stainless steel, chrome steel, and ceramic (silicon nitride, Si3N4).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] A hybrid ball bearing is a bearing with ceramic balls and metal races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] An *angular contact* ball bearing uses axially asymmetric races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] An axial load passes in a straight line through the bearing, whereas a radial load takes an oblique path that acts to separate the races axially.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] So, the angle of contact on the inner race is the same as that on the outer race.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Angular contact bearings better support combined loads (loading in both the radial and axial directions) and the contact angle of the bearing should be matched to the relative proportions of each.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The larger the contact angle (typically in the range 10 to 45 degrees), the higher the axial load supported, but the lower the radial load.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In high-speed applications, such as turbines, jet engines, and dentistry equipment, the centrifugal forces generated by the balls change the contact angle at the inner and outer race.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Ceramics such as silicon nitride are now regularly used in such applications due to their low density (40% of steel).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] These materials significantly reduce centrifugal force and function well in high temperature environments.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] They also tend to wear in a similar way to bearing steel—rather than cracking or shattering like glass or porcelain.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Most bicycles use angular-contact bearings in the headsets because the forces on these bearings are in both the radial and axial direction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] An *axial* or *thrust* ball bearing uses side-by-side races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] An axial load is transmitted directly through the bearing, while a radial load is poorly supported and tends to separate the races, so that a larger radial load is likely to damage the bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In a *deep-groove* radial bearing, the race dimensions are close to the dimensions of the balls that run in it.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Deep-groove bearings support higher loads than a shallower groove.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Like angular contact bearings, deep-groove bearings support both radial and axial loads, but without a choice of contact angle to allow choice of relative proportion of these load capacities.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The above basic types of bearings are typically applied in a method of *preloaded pairs*, where two individual bearings are rigidly fastened along a rotating shaft to face each other.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This improves the axial runout by taking up (*preloading*) the necessary slight clearance between the bearing balls and races.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Pairing also provides an advantage of evenly distributing the loads, nearly doubling the total load capacity compared to a single bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Angular contact bearings are almost always used in opposing pairs: the asymmetric design of each bearing supports axial loads in only one direction, so an opposed pair is required if the application demands support in both directions.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The preloading force must be designed and assembled carefully, because it deducts from the axial force capacity of the bearings and can damage bearings if applied excessively.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The pairing mechanism may simply face the bearings together directly, or separate them with a shim, bushing, or shaft feature.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] These bearings are assembled by placing the inner ring into an eccentric position relative to the outer ring, with the two rings in contact at one point, resulting in a large gap opposite the point of contact.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The balls are inserted through the gap and then evenly distributed around the bearing assembly, causing the rings to become concentric.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Assembly is completed by fitting a cage to the balls to maintain their positions relative to each other.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Without the cage, the balls would eventually drift out of position during operation, causing the bearing to fail.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The cage carries no load and serves only to maintain ball position.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Conrad bearings have the advantage that they are able to withstand both radial and axial loads but have the disadvantage of lower load capacity due to the limited number of balls that can be loaded into the bearing assembly.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Probably the most familiar industrial ball bearing is the deep-groove Conrad style.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The bearing is used in most of the mechanical industries.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] radial bearing, the inner and outer races are notched on one face so that when the notches are aligned, balls can be slipped in the resulting slot to assemble the bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] design), resulting in a higher radial load capacity than a Conrad bearing of the same dimensions and material type.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] However, a slot-fill bearing cannot carry a significant axial load, and the slots cause a discontinuity in the races that can have a small but adverse effect on strength.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Relieved race ball bearings are 'relieved' as the name suggests by having either the OD of the inner ring reduced on one side, or the ID of the outer ring increased on one side.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This allows a greater number of balls to be assembled into either the inner or outer race, and then press fit over the relief.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Sometimes the outer ring will be heated to facilitate assembly.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Like the slot-fill construction, relieved race construction allows a greater number of balls than Conrad construction, up to and including full complement, and the extra ball count gives extra load capacity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] However, a relieved race bearing can only support significant axial loads in one direction ('away from' the relieved race).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Another way of fitting more balls into a radial ball bearing is by radially 'fracturing' (slicing) one of the rings all the way through, loading the balls in, re-assembling the fractured portion, and then using a pair of steel bands to hold the fractured ring sections together in alignment.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Again, this allows more balls, including full ball complement, however unlike with either slot fill or relieved race constructions, it can support significant axial loading in either direction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Four wire rings are arranged in a square, to contact four points on a ball bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The wire rings are bearing steel and are ground smooth where they contact the bearing balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The wires cannot support bearing loads directly, so are placed in a housing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The housing may be a material which is not suitable for bearings but has other useful properties.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For example, wires in an aluminum housing may be lighter than a similar-size bearing made entirely of steel.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Most ball bearings are a single-row design, which means there is one row of bearing balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This design works with radial and thrust loads.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Advantages of double-row bearings as compared to single-row include that they can bear radial and axial loads in both directions.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Double-row angular contact ball bearings have a steep mounting, which also can bear tilting effects.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Other advantages of double-row bearings are their rigidity and compactness.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Their disadvantage is they need better alignment than single-row bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Bearings with a flange on the outer ring simplify axial location.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The housing for such bearings can consist of a through-hole of uniform diameter, but the entry face of the housing (which may be either the outer or inner face) must be machined truly normal to the hole axis.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] However, such flanges are very expensive to manufacture.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] A more cost-effective arrangement of the bearing outer ring, with similar benefits, is a snap ring groove at either or both ends of the outside diameter.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The snap ring assumes the function of a flange.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Cages are typically used to secure the balls in a Conrad-style ball bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In other construction types they may decrease the number of balls depending on the specific cage shape, and thus reduce the load capacity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Without cages the tangential position is stabilized by sliding of two convex surfaces on each other.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] With a cage the tangential position is stabilized by a sliding of a convex surface in a matched concave surface, which avoids dents in the balls and has lower friction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] in the mid-18th century as part of his work on chronographs.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Ceramic bearing balls can weigh up to 40% less than steel ones, depending on size and material.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This reduces centrifugal loading and skidding, so hybrid ceramic bearings can operate 20% to 40% faster than conventional bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This means that the outer race groove exerts less force inward against the ball as the bearing spins.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The lighter balls allow the bearing to spin faster, and uses less power to maintain its speed.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The ceramic balls are typically harder than the race.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Due to wear, with time they will form a groove in the race.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This is preferable to the balls wearing which would leave them with possible flat spots significantly harming performance.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] While the ceramic material itself is stronger than steel, it is also stiffer, which results in increased stresses on the rings, and hence decreased load capacity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Ceramic balls are electrically insulating, which can prevent 'arcing' failures if current should be passed through the bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Ceramic balls can also be effective in environments where lubrication may not be available (such as in space applications).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In some settings only a thin coating of ceramic is used over a metal ball bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] These bearings make use of both ceramic balls and race.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] These bearings are impervious to corrosion and rarely require lubrication if at all.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Due to the stiffness and hardness of the balls and race these bearings are noisy at high speeds.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The stiffness of the ceramic makes these bearings brittle and liable to crack under load or impact.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Because both ball and race are of similar hardness, wear can lead to chipping at high speeds of both the balls and the race, which can cause sparking.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] bearing shown in the picture, are constructed with the inner ring and ball assembly contained within an outer ring that has a spherical raceway.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] This construction allows the bearing to tolerate a small angular misalignment resulting from shaft or housing deflections or improper mounting.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The bearing was used mainly in bearing arrangements with very long shafts, such as transmission shafts in textile factories.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] One drawback of the self-aligning ball bearings is a limited load rating, as the outer raceway has very low osculation (its radius is much larger than the ball radius).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] , which has a similar design, but uses rollers instead of balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The calculated life for a bearing is based on the load it carries and its operating speed.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The industry standard usable bearing lifespan is inversely proportional to the bearing load cubed.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Nominal maximum load of a bearing, is for a lifespan of 1 million rotations, which at 50 Hz (i.e., 3000 RPM) is a lifespan of 5.5 working hours.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] 90% of bearings of that type have at least that lifespan, and 50% of bearings have a lifespan at least 5 times as long.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The industry standard life calculation is based upon the work of Lundberg and Palmgren performed in 1947.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The formula assumes the life to be limited by metal fatigue and that the life distribution can be described by a Weibull distribution.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Many variations of the formula exist that include factors for material properties, lubrication, and loading.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Factoring for loading may be viewed as a tacit admission that modern materials demonstrate a different relationship between load and life than Lundberg and Palmgren determined .
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If a bearing is not rotating, maximum load is determined by force that causes plastic deformation of elements or raceways.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The indentations caused by the elements can concentrate stresses and generate cracks at the components.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Maximum load for not or very slowly rotating bearings is called "static" maximum load.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Also, if a bearing is not rotating, oscillating forces on the bearing can cause impact damage to the bearing race or the rolling elements, known as brinelling.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] A second lesser form called false brinelling occurs if the bearing only rotates across a short arc and pushes lubricant out away from the rolling elements.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For a rotating bearing, the dynamic load capacity indicates the load to which the bearing endures 1,000,000 cycles.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If a bearing is rotating, but experiences heavy load that lasts shorter than one revolution, static max load must be used in computations, since the bearing does not rotate during the maximum load.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If a sideways torque is applied to a deep groove radial bearing, an uneven force in the shape of an ellipse is applied on the outer ring by the rolling elements, concentrating in two regions on opposite sides of the outer ring.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If the outer ring is not strong enough, or if it is not sufficiently braced by the supporting structure, the outer ring will deform into an oval shape from the sideways torque stress, until the gap is large enough for the rolling elements to escape.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The inner ring then pops out and the bearing structurally collapses.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] A sideways torque on a radial bearing also applies pressure to the cage that holds the rolling elements at equal distances, due to the rolling elements trying to all slide together at the location of highest sideways torque.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If the cage collapses or breaks apart, the rolling elements group together, the inner ring loses support, and may pop out of the center.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In general, maximum load on a ball bearing is proportional to outer diameter of the bearing times the width of the bearing (where width is measured in direction of axle).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] These are based on not exceeding a certain amount of plastic deformation in the raceway.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] These ratings may be exceeded by a large amount for certain applications.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For a bearing to operate properly, it needs to be lubricated.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In most cases the lubricant is based on elastohydrodynamic effect (by oil or grease) but working at extreme temperatures dry lubricated bearings are also available.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For a bearing to have its nominal lifespan at its nominal maximum load, it must be lubricated with a lubricant (oil or grease) that has at least the minimum dynamic viscosity (usually denoted with the Greek letter $\nu$ ) recommended for that bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The recommended dynamic viscosity is inversely proportional to diameter of bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The recommended dynamic viscosity decreases with rotating frequency.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] As a rough indication: for less than 3000 RPM, recommended viscosity increases with factor 6 for a factor 10 decrease in speed, and for more than 3000 RPM, recommended viscosity decreases with factor 3 for a factor 10 increase in speed.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For a bearing where average of outer diameter of bearing and diameter of axle hole is 50 mm, and that is rotating at 3000 RPM, recommended dynamic viscosity is 12 mm2/s.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Note that dynamic viscosity of oil varies strongly with temperature: a temperature increase of 50–70 °C causes the viscosity to decrease by factor 10.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If the viscosity of lubricant is higher than recommended, lifespan of bearing increases, roughly proportional to square root of viscosity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If the viscosity of the lubricant is lower than recommended, the lifespan of the bearing decreases, and by how much depends on which type of oil being used.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For oils with EP ('extreme pressure') additives, the lifespan is proportional to the square root of dynamic viscosity, just as it was for too high viscosity, while for ordinary oils lifespan is proportional to the square of the viscosity if a lower-than-recommended viscosity is used.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Lubrication can be done with a grease, which has advantages that grease is normally held within the bearing releasing the lubricant oil as it is compressed by the balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] It provides a protective barrier for the bearing metal from the environment, but has disadvantages that this grease must be replaced periodically, and maximum load of bearing decreases (because if bearing gets too warm, grease melts and runs out of bearing).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Time between grease replacements decreases very strongly with diameter of bearing: for a 40 mm bearing, grease should be replaced every 5000 working hours, while for a 100 mm bearing it should be replaced every 500 working hours.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Lubrication can also be done with an oil, which has advantage of higher maximum load, but needs some way to keep oil in bearing, as it normally tends to run out of it.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For oil lubrication it is recommended that for applications where oil does not become warmer than 50 °C, oil should be replaced once a year, while for applications where oil does not become warmer than 100 °C, oil should be replaced 4 times per year.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For car engines, oil becomes 100 °C but the engine has an oil filter to maintain oil quality; therefore, the oil is usually changed less frequently than the oil in bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If the bearing is used under oscillation, oil lubrication should be preferred.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If grease lubrication is necessary, the composition should be adapted to the parameters that occur.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Greases with a high bleeding rate and low base oil viscosity should be preferred if possible.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Most bearings are meant for supporting loads perpendicular to axle ("radial loads").
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Whether they can also bear axial loads, and if so, how much, depends on the type of bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Thrust bearings (commonly found on lazy susans) are specifically designed for axial loads.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For single-row deep-groove ball bearings, SKF's documentation says that maximum axial load is circa 50% of maximum radial load, but it also says that "light" and/or "small" bearings can take axial loads that are 25% of maximum radial load.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For single-row edge-contact ball bearings, axial load can be about 2 times max radial load, and for cone-bearings maximum axial load is between 1 and 2 times maximum radial load.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Often Conrad-style ball bearings will exhibit contact ellipse truncation under axial load.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] That means that either the ID of the outer ring is large enough, or the OD of the inner ring is small enough, so as to reduce the area of contact between the balls and raceway.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] When this is the case, it can significantly increase the stresses in the bearing, often invalidating rules of thumb regarding relationships between radial and axial load capacity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] With construction types other than Conrad, one can further decrease the outer ring ID and increase the inner ring OD to guard against this.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If both axial and radial loads are present, they can be added vectorially, to result in the total load on bearing, which in combination with nominal maximum load can be used to predict lifespan.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] However, in order to correctly predict the rating life of ball bearings the ISO/TS 16281 should be used with the help of a calculation software.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The part of a bearing that rotates (either axle hole or outer circumference) must be fixed, while for a part that does not rotate this is not necessary (so it can be allowed to slide).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If a bearing is loaded axially, both sides must be fixed.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If an axle has two bearings, and temperature varies, axle shrinks or expands, therefore it is not admissible for both bearings to be fixed on both their sides, since expansion of axle would exert axial forces that would destroy these bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Therefore, at least one of the bearings must be able to slide.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] A 'freely sliding fit' is one where there is at least a 4 μm clearance, presumably because surface-roughness of a surface made on a lathe is normally between 1.6 and 3.2 μm.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Bearings can withstand their maximum load only if the mating parts are properly sized.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Bearing manufacturers supply tolerances for the fit of the shaft and the housing so that this can be achieved.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The material and hardness may also be specified.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Fittings that are not allowed to slip are made to diameters that prevent slipping and consequently the mating surfaces cannot be brought into position without force.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For small bearings this is best done with a press because tapping with a hammer damages both bearing and shaft, while for large bearings the necessary forces are so great that there is no alternative to heating one part before fitting, so that thermal expansion allows a temporary sliding fit.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] If a shaft is supported by two bearings, and the center-lines of rotation of these bearings are not the same, then large forces are exerted on the bearing, which may destroy it.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Some very small amount of misalignment is acceptable, and how much depends on type of bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] For bearings that are specifically made to be 'self-aligning', acceptable misalignment is between 1.5 and 3 degrees of arc.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] Bearings that are not designed to be self-aligning can accept misalignment of only 2–10 minutes of arc (0.033-0.166 degrees) .
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] In general, ball bearings are used in most applications that involve moving parts.
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The ball size increases as the series increases, for any given inner diameter or outer diameter (not both).
[src:ball-screw/ball-bearing] The larger the ball the greater the load carrying capacity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A **ball screw** (or **ballscrew**) is a mechanical linear actuator that translates rotational motion to linear motion with little friction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A threaded shaft provides a helical raceway for ball bearings which act as a precision screw.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] As well as being able to apply or withstand high thrust loads, they can do so with minimum internal friction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] They are made to close tolerances and are therefore suitable for high-precision applications.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The ball assembly acts as the nut while the threaded shaft is the screw.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] In contrast to conventional leadscrews, ball screws tend to be rather bulky, due to the need to have a mechanism to recirculate the balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The ball screw was invented independently by H.M.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Glenn who were issued in 1898 patents 601,451 and 610,044 respectively.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Early precise screwshafts were produced by starting with a low-precision screwshaft, and then lapping the shaft with several spring-loaded nut laps..
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] By rearranging and inverting the nut laps, the lengthwise errors of the nuts and shaft were averaged.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Then, the repeatable pitch shaft's pitch is measured against a distance standard.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A similar process is sometimes used today to produce reference standard screw shafts and to master manufacturing screw shafts.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Low friction in ball screws yields high mechanical efficiency compared to alternatives.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A typical ball screw may be 90 percent efficient, versus 20 to 25 percent efficiency of an Acme lead screw of equal size.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Lack of sliding friction between the nut and screw lends itself to extended lifespan of the screw assembly (especially in no-backlash systems), reducing downtime for maintenance and parts replacement, while also decreasing demand for lubrication.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] This, combined with their overall performance benefits and reduced power requirements, may offset the initial costs of using ball screws.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Ball screws may also reduce or eliminate the backlash common in lead screw and nut combinations.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The balls may be preloaded so that there is no "wiggle" between the ball screw and ball nut.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] This is particularly desirable in applications where the load on the screw varies quickly, such as machine tools.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Because of their high mechanical efficiency, especially compared to traditional lead screws, ball screws can potentially be back-driven (that is, a linear force applied directly to the nut can induce a rotation of the shaft, an effect counterproductive to most uses).
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] While this is usually of limited consequence to motorized applications, and potentially even provides a mild protective effect in some cases, it makes them generally unsuitable for application in manually actuated systems, such as hand-fed machine tools.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The static torque and digital control of an appropriate servomotor can be made to resist and compensate, but hand cranked mechanisms would require additional mechanisms to prevent undesirable behaviors.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Because an ordinary lead screw resists or even prohibits such reverse operation, they are inherently safer and more reliable for manual use.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The magnitude of force needed to consequentially back-drive an Acme lead screw would usually be sufficient to destroy the mechanism, immobilizing the machine and absorbing any dangerous force before it could pose a risk to an operator.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The circulating balls travel inside the thread form of the screw and nut, and balls are recirculated through various types of return mechanisms.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] If the ball nut did not have a return mechanism, then the balls would fall out of the end of the ball nut when they reached the end of the nut.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] For this reason several different recirculation methods have been developed.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] An *external ballnut* employs a stamped tube which picks up balls from the raceway by use of a small pick-up finger.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Balls travel inside the tube and are then replaced back into the thread raceway.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] An *internal-button ballnut* employs a machined or cast button-style return which allows balls to exit the raceway track and move one thread then reenter the raceway.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] An *endcap return ball* nut employs a cap on the end of the ball nut.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The cap is machined to pick up balls coming out of the end of the nut and direct them down holes which are bored transversely down the ballnut.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The complement cap on the other side of the nut directs balls back into the raceway.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The returning balls are not under significant mechanical load and the return path may incorporate injection-moulded low-friction plastic parts.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A ball screw involves significantly more parts and surface interactions than many similar systems.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] While a basic lead screw is composed of only a solid shaft and a solid nut with simple mating geometries, a ball screw requires precisely formed curved contours and multi-part assemblies to facilitate the action of the bearing balls.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] This makes them more expensive to manufacture and sometimes to maintain, and provides more potential avenues for failure if the apparatus is not properly cared for.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] if the linear force is backdriving the system.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] In these equations, ${\mathit {T}}$ is the torque applied to screw or nut, ${\mathit {F}}$ is the linear force applied, ${\mathit {l}}$ is the ball screw lead, and $\nu$ is the ball screw efficiency.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Selection of the standard to be used is an agreement between the supplier and the user and has some significance in the design of the screw.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] In the United States, ASME has developed the B5.48-1977 Standard entitled "Ball Screws".
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The correct evaluation of the curvatures of ball screw grooves allows one to accurately design the constructive parameters of this mechanism and to enhance its performance.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The formulation commonly used in literature refers to the ball bearing's geometry, ignoring the shape of the section's profile and the helix angle.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The second principal curvature is simply $\kappa _{2s}=-{\frac {1}{2f_{s}r_{b}}}$ for the screw shaft groove and $\kappa _{2n}=-{\frac {1}{2f_{n}r_{b}}}$ for the nut groove, where $f_{s}$ and $f_{n}$ are, respectively, the conformity factors of the groove profiles of the screw shaft and nut.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] These formulations do not take into account the shape of the groove profiles and the presence of the helix angle: more recent publications found the exact solution for the curvature of the grooves of screw shaft and nut.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A new research proposes a new formulation which approximates the real curvature values with a maximum relative error of approximately 0.5%.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] To maintain their inherent accuracy and ensure long life, great care is needed to avoid contamination with dirt and abrasive particles.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] This may be achieved by using rubber or leather bellows to completely or partially enclose the working surfaces.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Another solution is to use a positive pressure of filtered air when they are used in a semi-sealed or open enclosure.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] While reducing friction, ball screws can operate with some preload, effectively eliminating backlash (slop) between input (rotation) and output (linear motion).
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] This feature is essential when they are used in computer-controlled motion-control systems, such as CNC machine tools and high precision motion applications (such as wire bonding).
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] To obtain proper rolling action of the balls, as in a standard ball bearing, it is necessary that, when loaded in one direction, the ball makes contact at one point with the nut, and one point with the screw.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] In practice, most ball screws are designed to be lightly preloaded, so that there is at least a slight load on the ball at four points, two in contact with the nut and two in contact with the screw.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] To this end, the threads are usually machined as a "gothic arch" profile.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] If a simple semicircular thread profile were used, contact would only be at two points, on the outer and inner edges, which would not resist axial loading.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] To remove backlash and obtain the optimum stiffness and wear characteristics for a given application, a controlled amount of preload is usually applied.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] This is accomplished in some cases by machining the components such that the balls are a "tight" fit when assembled; however, this gives poor control of the preload, and cannot be adjusted to allow for wear.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Ball screw shafts may be fabricated by rolling, yielding a less precise but inexpensive and mechanically efficient product.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Rolled ball screws have a positional precision of several thousandths of an inch per foot.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Ball screws are classified using "accuracy grades" from C0 (most precise) to C10.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] High-precision screw shafts are typically precise to one thousandth of an inch per foot (830 nm/cm) or better.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] They have historically been machined to gross shape, case-hardened, and then ground.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The three-step process is needed because high-temperature machining distorts the workpiece.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Hard whirling is a recent (2008) precision machining technique that minimizes heating of the work, and can produce precision screws from case-hardened bar stock.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Instrument-quality screw shafts are typically precise to 250 nanometers per centimeter.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] They are produced on precision milling machines with optical distance measuring equipment and special tooling.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Similar machines are used to produce optical lenses and mirrors.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Instrument screw shafts are generally made of Invar, to prevent temperature from changing tolerances too much.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Ball screws are used in aircraft and missiles to move control surfaces, especially for electric fly by wire, and in automobile power steering to translate rotary motion from an electric motor to axial motion of the steering rack.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] They are also used in machine tools, robots, and precision assembly equipment.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] High-precision ball screws are used in steppers for semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A ball screw is used to expand the Deployable Tower Assembly (DTA) structure on the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] A ball screw is also planned to be used in TerraPower's Natrium Reactor as part of its Control rod drive mechanism.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] Another form of linear actuator based on a rotating rod is the threadless ballscrew, or "rolling ring drive".
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] In this design, three or more rolling-ring bearings are arranged symmetrically in a housing surrounding a smooth (threadless) actuator rod or shaft.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] The bearings are set at an angle to the rod, and this angle determines the direction and rate of linear motion per revolution of the rod.
[src:ball-screw/ball-screw] An advantage of this design over the conventional ballscrew or leadscrew is the practical elimination of backlash and loading caused by preload nuts.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] A **linear-motion bearing** or **linear slide** is a bearing designed to provide free motion in one direction.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] There are many different types of linear motion bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Motorized linear slides such as machine slides, X-Y tables, roller tables and some dovetail slides are bearings moved by drive mechanisms.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Not all linear slides are motorized, and non-motorized dovetail slides, ball bearing slides and roller slides provide low-friction linear movement for equipment powered by inertia or by hand.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] All linear slides provide linear motion based on bearings, whether they are ball bearings, dovetail bearings, linear roller bearings, magnetic or fluid bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] X-Y tables, linear stages, machine slides and other advanced slides use linear motion bearings to provide movement along both X and Y multiple axis.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] A rolling-element bearing is generally composed of a sleeve-like outer ring and several rows of balls retained by cages.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] The cages were originally machined from solid metal and were quickly replaced by stampings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] It features smooth motion, low friction, high rigidity and long life.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] They are economical, and easy to maintain and replace.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Thomson Industries (currently owned by Altra Industrial Motion) is generally given credit for first producing [what is now known as] a linear ball bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Rolling-element bearings are manufactured in two forms: ball bearing slides and roller slides.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Also called "ball slides," ball bearing slides are the most common type of linear slide.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Ball bearing slides offer smooth precision motion along a single-axis linear design, aided by ball bearings housed in the linear base, with self-lubrication properties that increase reliability.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Ball bearing slide applications include delicate instrumentation, robotic assembly, cabinetry, high-end appliances and clean room environments, which primarily serve the manufacturing industry but also the furniture, electronics and construction industries.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] For example, a widely used ball bearing slide in the furniture industry is a ball bearing drawer slide.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] This low-friction linear movement can be powered by either a drive mechanism, inertia or by hand.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Ball bearing slides tend to have a lower load capacity for their size compared to other linear slides because the balls are less resistant to wear and abrasions.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] In addition, ball bearing slides are limited by the need to fit into housing or drive systems.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] The travelling distance of linear recirculating ball bearings is only limited by the length of their rail, as the balls recirculate inside the bearing's housing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Linear non-recirculating ball bearings have balls installed on a bracket and only move in one axis without recirculation.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Since the balls do not recirculate, this type of bearings can provide extremely smooth motion.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] However, the travelling distance of linear non-recirculating ball bearings is limited by the length of the bracket.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Also known as crossed roller slides, roller slides are non-motorized linear slides that provide low-friction linear movement for equipment powered by inertia or by hand.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Roller slides are based on linear roller bearings, which are frequently criss-crossed to provide heavier load capabilities and better movement control.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Serving industries such as manufacturing, photonics, medical and telecommunications, roller slides are versatile and can be adjusted to meet numerous applications which typically include clean rooms, vacuum environments, material handling and automation machinery.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Roller slides work similarly to ball bearing slides, except that the bearings housed within the carriage are cylinder-shaped instead of ball shaped.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] The rollers crisscross each other at a 90° angle and move between the four semi-flat and parallel rods that surround the rollers.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] The rollers are between "V" grooved bearing races, one being on the top carriage and the other on the base.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Typically, bearing housings are constructed from aluminum while the rollers are constructed from steel.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Although roller slides are not self-cleaning, they are suitable for environments with low levels of airborne contaminants such as dirt and dust.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] As one of the more expensive types of linear slides, roller slides are capable of providing linear motion on more than one axis through stackable slides and double carriages.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Roller slides offers line contact versus point contact as with ball bearings, creating a broader contact surface due to the consistency of contact between the carriage and the base and resulting in less erosion.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Plain bearings are very similar in design to rolling-element bearings, except they slide without the use of ball bearings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] If they are cylindrical in shape, they are often called bushings.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Bushings can be metal or plastic, or even air.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Dovetail slides, or dovetail way slides are typically constructed from cast iron, but can also be constructed from hard-coat aluminum, acetal or stainless steel.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Like any bearing, a dovetail slide is composed of a stationary linear base and a moving carriage. a Dovetail carriage has a v-shaped, or dovetail-shaped protruding channel which locks into the linear base's correspondingly shaped groove.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Once the dovetail carriage is fitted into its base's channel, the carriage is locked into the channel's linear axis and allows free linear movement.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] When a platform is attached to the carriage of a dovetail slide, a dovetail table is created, offering extended load carrying capabilities.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Dovetail slides are advantageous when it comes to load capacity, affordability and durability.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Capable of long travel, dovetail slides are more resistant to shock than other bearings, and they are mostly immune to chemical, dust and dirt contamination.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Dovetail slides can be motorized, mechanical or electromechanical.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Electric dovetail slides are driven by a number of different devices, such as ball screws, belts and cables, which are powered by functional motors such as stepper motors, linear motors and handwheels.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Dovetail slides are direct contact systems, making them fitting for heavy load applications including CNC machines, shuttle devices, special machines and work holding devices.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Mainly used in the manufacturing and laboratory science industries, dovetail slides are ideal for high-precision applications.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Slides can be constructed with two sections or multiple sections.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] A slide with two sections can only extend approximately 3/4 of the total compressed slide length.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] A compound slide typically has three sections: fixed, floating intermediate member, and the section attached to the equipment.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] A compound slide can extend at least as far as the compressed slide length and typically a bit more.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] In the case of rack slides, this allows the equipment to extend completely out of the rack allowing access for service or connection of cables and such to the back of the equipment.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Rack slides are specifically intended for mounting equipment into 19-inch racks or 23-inch racks.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] These can be friction bearing, ball bearing, or roller bearing.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] They are sized to fit into racks with mounting flanges on the ends to mate to the mounting holes in racks.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] In some cases, one mounting flange is formed into the rack slide with an adapter bracket attached to the other end to accommodate different depths of the rack.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] The outer fixed member is attached to the rack and the inner moving member is generally screwed to the side of the mounted equipment.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Rack slides are typically compound or 3-part slides allowing full extension of the mounted equipment and generally include provision for sliding the inner member completely free to allow removal of the equipment from the rack.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] They can also include stops to prevent accidentally pulling the equipment out of the rack without releasing the stop mechanism.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] There can be proprietary configurations which, for example, may clip to the equipment without the use of screws or can be clipped into an appropriately designed rack.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] But the basic geometry is the same regardless of how they are mounted.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Ball splines (ball spline bearings) are a special type of linear motion bearing that are used to provide nearly frictionless linear motion while allowing the member to transmit torque simultaneously.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] There are grooves ground along the length of the shaft (thus forming splines) for the ball bearings to run inside.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] The outer shell that houses the balls is called a nut rather than a bushing, but is not a nut in the traditional sense—it is not free to rotate about the shaft, but is free to travel up and down the shaft.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] For a shaft travel of any significant length the nut will have channels that recirculate the balls, operating in the same way as a ball screw.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] By increasing the contact area of the ball bearings on the shaft to approximately 45 degrees, the side load and direct load carrying capabilities are greatly increased.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] Each nut can be individually preloaded at the factory to decrease the available radial play to ensure rigidity.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] This process not only increases the contact area, increasing direct loading capabilities, but it also restricts any radial movement, increasing the overhung moment capabilities.
[src:ball-screw/ball-spline] This creates a sturdier structure that can handle a very strenuous working environment.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The term "bellows" is used by extension for a flexible bag whose volume can be changed by compression or expansion, but not used to deliver air.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] For example, the light-tight (but not airtight) bag allowing the distance between the lens and film of a folding photographic camera to be varied is called a bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The Old English name for "bellows" was *blǽstbęl(i)g*, *blást-bęl(i)g* 'blast-bag', 'blowing-bag'; the prefix was dropped and by the eleventh century the simple *bęlg*, *bylg*, *bylig* ('bag') was used.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] There are similar words in Old Norse, Swedish, and Danish and Dutch (blaasbalg), but the derivation is not certain.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] 'Bellows' appears not to be cognate with the superficially similar Latin follis.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Several processes, such as metallurgical iron smelting and welding, require so much heat that they could only be developed after the invention, in antiquity, of the bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The bellows are used to deliver additional air to the fuel, raising the rate of combustion and therefore the heat output.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Chinese bellows were originally made of ox hide with two pots as described in Mozi's book on military technology in the Warring States period (4th century BC).
[src:ball-screw/bellows] By the Han dynasty, contact with Southeast Asian cultures exposed the Chinese to the bamboo-based piston bellows of Southeast Asians.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The acquired piston bellows technology completely replaced the Chinese ox hide bellows that by the Song dynasty, the ox hide bellows were completely extinct.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The Han dynasty Chinese mechanical engineer Du Shi (d.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] 38) is credited with being the first to use hydraulic power on a double-action piston pumps, through a waterwheel, to operate bellows in metallurgy.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] His invention was used to operate piston bellows of blast furnaces in order to forge cast iron.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The ancient Greeks, ancient Romans, and other civilizations used bellows in bloomery furnaces producing wrought iron.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Bellows are also used to send pressurized air in a controlled manner in a fired heater.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] In modern industry, reciprocating bellows are usually replaced with motorized blowers.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] These bellows blow a more constant, and thus stronger, blast than simple bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Such bellows existed in China at least since the 5th century BC, when it was invented, and had reached Europe by the 16th century.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] In 240 BC, The ancient Greek inventor Ctesibius of Alexandria independently invented a double-action piston bellow used to lift water from one level to another.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] A piston is enclosed in a rectangular box with a handle coming out one side.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The piston edges are covered with feathers, fur, or soft paper to ensure that it is airtight and lubricated.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] As the piston is pulled, air enters from the far side and the air in the near chamber is compressed and forced into a side chamber, where it flows through the nozzle.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Then as it is pushed air enters from the near side and the air in the far chamber flows through the same nozzle.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The top leaf can move freely and has a weight on it.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The bottom and the middle leaves contain valves, the top one does not.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Only the top lung is connected to the spout.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] When the bottom leaf is moved up, air is pumped from the bottom lung into the top lung.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] At the same time air is leaving the bellows from the top lung through the spout, but at a slower rate.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Next the bottom leaf is moved down to pull fresh air into the bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] While this happens the weight on the top leaf pushes it down, so air keeps leaving through the spout.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] This design does not increase the amount of air flow going into the forge, but provides a more constant air flow compared to a simple bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] It also provides more even air flow than two simple bellows pumped alternately or one double-acting piston bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] In archaeological ruins of the Levant, archaeologists have found primitive pot bellows, consisting of a ceramic pot to which a loose leather hide had been attached at the top.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Such pot bellows were constructed with a wide rim, so that the hide covering would transmit a maximum amount of air when pumped.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The covering was fastened to the pot with a cord under an out-turned rim, or in a groove just below the rim exterior.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] An opening near the base served to insert a pipe of perishable material whose purpose was to direct the air blast to either the furnace or crucible, and which was usually done through the mediation of a tuyère.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Tuyères used in conjunction with pot bellows had the function of protecting the ends of perishable tubes leading from the pot into the fire.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Places in Saharan Africa still make use of primitive pot bellows.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] The term "bellows" is used by extension for a number of applications that do not involve air transfer.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Bee smokers have bellows attached to the side to provide air to a slow burning fuel.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] This allows for an increased rate of combustion and a temporarily higher output of smoke on command, something desirable when calming domesticated bees.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Bellows are also designed as air foot pumps to blow up inflatables.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] High volume foot pumps (4-7 litres per stroke) are used for large inflatables, such as airbeds, inflatable sofas, paddling pools or large inflatable toys; with large amounts of air flowed into the large inflatable per step, the pumping time is reduced.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] However, the highest litre per stroke can require more effort despite less time.
[src:ball-screw/bellows] Low volume pumps (3 litres or less) are used for smaller inflatables, such as bike tyres, footballs, small inflatable toys, or pool mattresses - these are not to be used on large inflatables as compressing can be repetitive and time consuming.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A **belt** is a loop of flexible material used to link two or more rotating shafts mechanically, most often parallel.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts may be used as a source of motion, to transmit power efficiently or to track relative movement.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts are looped over pulleys and may have a twist between the pulleys, and the shafts need not be parallel.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In a two pulley system, the belt can either drive the pulleys normally in one direction (the same if on parallel shafts), or the belt may be crossed, so that the direction of the driven shaft is reversed (the opposite direction to the driver if on parallel shafts).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The belt drive can also be used to change the speed of rotation, either up or down, by using different sized pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] As a source of motion, a conveyor belt is one application where the belt is adapted to carry a load continuously between two points.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The mechanical belt drive, using a pulley machine, was first mentioned in the text of the *Dictionary of Local Expressions* by the Han Dynasty philosopher, poet, and politician Yang Xiong (53–18 BC) in 15 BC, used for a quilling machine that wound silk fibres onto bobbins for weavers' shuttles.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The belt drive is an essential component of the invention of the spinning wheel.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The belt drive was not only used in textile technologies, it was also applied to hydraulic-powered bellows dated from the 1st century AD.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts are the cheapest utility for power transmission between shafts that may not be axially aligned.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Power transmission is achieved by purposely designed belts and pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The variety of power transmission needs that can be met by a belt-drive transmission system are numerous, and this has led to many variations on the theme.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt drives run smoothly and with little noise, and provide shock absorption for motors, loads, and bearings when the force and power needed changes.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A drawback to belt drives is that they transmit less power than gears or chain drives.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] However, improvements in belt engineering allow use of belts in systems that formerly only allowed chain drives or gears.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] where $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ are tensions in the tight side and slack side of the belt respectively.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] where $\mu$ is the coefficient of friction, and $\alpha$ is the angle (in radians) subtended by contact surface at the centre of the pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt drives are simple, inexpensive, and do not require axially aligned shafts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They help protect machinery from overload and jam, and damp and isolate noise and vibration.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Load fluctuations are shock-absorbed (cushioned).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They need no lubrication and minimal maintenance.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They have high efficiency (90–98%, usually 95%), high tolerance for misalignment, and are of relatively low cost if the shafts are far apart.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Clutch action can be achieved by shifting the belt to a free turning pulley or by releasing belt tension.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Different speeds can be obtained by stepped or tapered pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The angular-velocity ratio may not be exactly constant or equal to that of the pulley diameters, due to slip and stretch.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] However, this problem can be largely solved by the use of toothed belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Working temperatures range from −35 to 85 °C (−31 to 185 °F).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Adjustment of centre distance or addition of an idler pulley is crucial to compensate for wear and stretch.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Flat belts were widely used in the 19th and early 20th centuries in line shafting to transmit power in factories.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They were also used in countless farming, mining, and logging applications, such as bucksaws, sawmills, threshers, silo blowers, conveyors for filling corn cribs or haylofts, balers, water pumps (for wells, mines, or swampy farm fields), and electrical generators.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Flat belts are still used today, although not nearly as much as in the line-shaft era.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The flat belt is a simple system of power transmission that was well suited for its day.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] It can deliver high power at high speeds (373 kW at 51 m/s; 115 mph), in cases of wide belts and large pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Wide-belt-large-pulley drives are bulky, consuming much space while requiring high tension, leading to high loads, and are poorly suited to close-centers applications.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] V-belts have mainly replaced flat belts for short-distance power transmission; and longer-distance power transmission is typically no longer done with belts at all.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] For example, factory machines now tend to have individual electric motors.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Because flat belts tend to climb towards the higher side of the pulley, pulleys were made with a slightly convex or "crowned" surface (rather than flat) to allow the belt to self-center as it runs.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Flat belts also tend to slip on the pulley face when heavy loads are applied, and many proprietary belt dressings were available that could be applied to the belts to increase friction, and so power transmission.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Flat belts were traditionally made of leather or fabric.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Early flour mills in Ukraine had leather belt drives.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] After World War I, there was such a shortage of shoe leather that people cut up the belt drives to make shoes.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Selling shoes was more profitable than selling flour for a time.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Flour milling soon came to a standstill and bread prices rose, contributing to famine conditions.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Leather drive belts were put to another use during the Rhodesian Bush War (1964–1979): To protect riders of cars and busses from land mines, layers of leather belt drives were placed on the floors of vehicles in danger zones.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Today most belt drives are made of rubber or synthetic polymers.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Grip of leather belts is often better if they are assembled with the hair side (outer side) of the leather against the pulley, although some belts are instead given a half-twist before joining the ends (forming a Möbius strip), so that wear can be evenly distributed on both sides of the belt.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts ends are joined by lacing the ends together with leather thonging (the oldest of the methods), steel comb fasteners and/or lacing, or by gluing or welding (in the case of polyurethane or polyester).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Flat belts were traditionally jointed, and still usually are, but they can also be made with endless construction.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In the mid 19th century, British millwrights discovered that multi-grooved pulleys connected by ropes outperformed flat pulleys connected by leather belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Wire ropes were occasionally used, but cotton, hemp, manila hemp and flax rope saw the widest use.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Typically, the rope connecting two pulleys with multiple V-grooves was spliced into a single loop that traveled along a helical path before being returned to its starting position by an idler pulley that also served to maintain the tension on the rope.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Sometimes, a single rope was used to transfer power from one multiple-groove drive pulley to several single- or multiple-groove driven pulleys in this way.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In general, as with flat belts, rope drives were used for connections from stationary engines to the jack shafts and line shafts of mills, and sometimes from line shafts to driven machinery.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Unlike leather belts, however, rope drives were sometimes used to transmit power over relatively long distances.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Over long distances, intermediate sheaves were used to support the "flying rope", and in the late 19th century, this was considered quite efficient.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Round belts are a circular cross section belt designed to run in a pulley with a 60 degree V-groove.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Round grooves are only suitable for idler pulleys that guide the belt, or when (soft) O-ring type belts are used.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The V-groove transmits torque through a wedging action, thus increasing friction.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Nevertheless, round belts are for use in relatively low torque situations only and may be purchased in various lengths or cut to length and joined, either by a staple, a metallic connector (in the case of hollow plastic), gluing or welding (in the case of polyurethane).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Early sewing machines utilized a leather belt, joined either by a metal staple or glued, to great effect.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Spring belts are similar to rope or round belts but consist of a long steel helical spring.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They are commonly found on toy or small model engines, typically steam engines driving other toys or models or providing a transmission between the crankshaft and other parts of a vehicle.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The main advantage over rubber or other elastic belts is that they last much longer under poorly controlled operating conditions.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The distance between the pulleys is also less critical.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Their main disadvantage is that slippage is more likely due to the lower coefficient of friction.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The ends of a spring belt can be joined either by bending the last turn of the helix at each end by 90 degrees to form hooks, or by reducing the diameter of the last few turns at one end so that it "screws" into the other end.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] V belts (also style V-belts, vee belts, or, less commonly, wedge rope) solved the slippage and alignment problem.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] It is now the basic belt for power transmission.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They provide the best combination of traction, speed of movement, load of the bearings, and long service life.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They are generally endless, and their general cross-section shape is roughly trapezoidal (hence the name "V").
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The "V" shape of the belt tracks in a mating groove in the pulley (or sheave), with the result that the belt cannot slip off.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The belt also tends to wedge into the groove as the load increases—the greater the load, the greater the wedging action—improving torque transmission and making the V-belt an effective solution, needing less width and tension than flat belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] V-belts trump flat belts with their small center distances and high reduction ratios.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The preferred center distance is larger than the largest pulley diameter, but less than three times the sum of both pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] V-belts need larger pulleys for their thicker cross-section than flat belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] For high-power requirements, two or more V-belts can be joined side-by-side in an arrangement called a multi-V, running on matching multi-groove sheaves.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] This is known as a multiple-V-belt drive (or sometimes a "classical V-belt drive").
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] V-belts may be homogeneously rubber or polymer throughout, or there may be fibers embedded in the rubber or polymer for strength and reinforcement.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The fibers may be of textile materials such as cotton, polyamide (such as nylon) or polyester or, for greatest strength, of steel or aramid (such as Technora, Twaron or Kevlar).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] When an endless belt does not fit the need, jointed and link V-belts may be employed.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Most models offer the same power and speed ratings as equivalently-sized endless belts and do not require special pulleys to operate.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A link v-belt is a number of polyurethane/polyester composite links held together, either by themselves, such as Fenner Drives' PowerTwist, or Nu-T-Link (with metal studs).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] These provide easy installation and superior environmental resistance compared to rubber belts and are length-adjustable by disassembling and removing links when needed.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Trade journal coverage of V-belts in automobiles from 1916 mentioned leather as the belt material, and mentioned that the V angle was not yet well standardized.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The endless rubber V-belt was developed in 1917 by Charles C.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Multiple-V-belt drive was first arranged a few years later by Walter Geist of the Allis-Chalmers corporation, who was inspired to replace the single rope of multi-groove-sheave rope drives with multiple V-belts running parallel.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Geist filed for a patent in 1925, and Allis-Chalmers began marketing the drive under the "Texrope" brand; the patent was granted in 1928 (U.S. patent 1,662,511).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The "Texrope" brand still exists, although it has changed ownership and no longer refers to multiple-V-belt drive alone.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A multi-groove, V-ribbed, or polygroove belt is made up of usually between 3 and 24 V-shaped sections alongside each other.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] This gives a thinner belt for the same drive surface, thus it is more flexible, although often wider.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The added flexibility offers an improved efficiency, as less energy is wasted in the internal friction of continually bending the belt.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In practice this gain of efficiency causes a reduced heating effect on the belt, and a cooler-running belt lasts longer in service.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts are commercially available in several sizes, with usually a 'P' (sometimes omitted) and a single letter identifying the pitch between grooves.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The 'PK' section with a pitch of 3.56 mm is commonly used for automotive applications.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A further advantage of the polygroove belt that makes them popular is that they can run over pulleys on the ungrooved back of the belt.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Though this is sometimes done with V-belts with a single idler pulley for tensioning, a polygroove belt may be wrapped around a pulley on its back tightly enough to change its direction, or even to provide a light driving force.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Any V-belt's ability to drive pulleys depends on wrapping the belt around a sufficient angle of the pulley to provide grip.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Where a single-V-belt is limited to a simple convex shape, it can adequately wrap at most three or possibly four pulleys, so can drive at most three accessories.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Where more must be driven, such as for modern cars with power steering and air conditioning, multiple belts are required.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] As the polygroove belt can be bent into concave paths by external idlers, it can wrap any number of driven pulleys, limited only by the power capacity of the belt.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] This ability to bend the belt at the designer's whim allows it to take a complex or "serpentine" path.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] This can assist the design of a compact engine layout, where the accessories are mounted more closely to the engine block and without the need to provide movable tensioning adjustments.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The entire belt may be tensioned by a single idler pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The nomenclature used for belt sizes varies by region and trade.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] An automotive belt with the number "740K6" or "6K740" indicates a belt 74 inches (190 cm) in length, 6 ribs wide, with a rib pitch of 9⁄64 of an inch (3.6 mm) (a standard thickness for a K series automotive belt would be 4.5mm).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A metric equivalent would be usually indicated by "6PK1880" whereby 6 refers to the number of ribs, PK refers to the metric PK thickness and pitch standard, and 1880 is the length of the belt in millimeters.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] A ribbed belt is a power transmission belt featuring lengthwise grooves.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] It operates from contact between the ribs of the belt and the grooves in the pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The ribbed belt may be fitted on various applications: compressors, fitness bikes, agricultural machinery, food mixers, washing machines, lawn mowers, etc.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Though often grouped with flat belts, they are actually a different kind.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They consist of a very thin belt (0.5–15 millimeters or 100–4000 micrometres) strip of plastic and occasionally rubber.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They are generally intended for low-power (less than 10 watts), high-speed uses, allowing high efficiency (up to 98%) and long life.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] These are seen in business machines, printers, tape recorders, and other light-duty operations.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Timing belts (also known as **toothed**, **notch**, **cog**, or **synchronous** belts) are a *positive* transfer belt and can track relative movement.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] These belts have teeth that fit into a matching toothed pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] When correctly tensioned, they have no slippage, run at constant speed, and are often used to transfer direct motion for indexing or timing purposes (hence their name).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] They are often used instead of chains or gears, so there is less noise and a lubrication bath is not necessary.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Camshafts of automobiles, miniature timing systems, and stepper motors often utilize these belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Timing belts need the least tension of all belts and are among the most efficient.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Timing belts with a helical offset tooth design are available.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The helical offset tooth design forms a chevron pattern and causes the teeth to engage progressively.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The chevron pattern design is self-aligning and does not make the noise that some timing belts make at certain speeds, and is more efficient at transferring power (up to 98%).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The advantages of timing belts include clean operation, energy efficiency, low maintenance, low noise, non slip performance, versatile load and speed capabilities.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts normally transmit power on the tension side of the loop.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] However, designs for continuously variable transmissions exist that use belts that are a series of solid metal blocks, linked together as in a chain, transmitting power on the compression side of the loop.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belts used for rolling roads for wind tunnels can be capable of 250 km/h (160 mph).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The open belt drive has parallel shafts rotating in the same direction, whereas the cross-belt drive also bears parallel shafts but rotate in opposite direction.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The former is far more common, and the latter not appropriate for timing and standard V-belts unless there is a twist between each pulley so that the pulleys only contact the same belt surface.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Nonparallel shafts can be connected if the belt's center line is aligned with the center plane of the pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Industrial belts are usually reinforced rubber but sometimes leather types.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Non-leather, non-reinforced belts can only be used in light applications.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The pitch line is the line between the inner and outer surfaces that is neither subject to tension (like the outer surface) nor compression (like the inner).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] It is midway through the surfaces in film and flat belts and dependent on cross-sectional shape and size in timing and V-belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Standard reference pitch diameter can be estimated by taking average of gear teeth tips diameter and gear teeth base diameter.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The angular speed is inversely proportional to size, so the larger the one wheel, the less angular velocity, and vice versa.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Actual pulley speeds tend to be 0.5–1% less than generally calculated because of belt slip and stretch.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In timing belts, the inverse ratio teeth of the belt contributes to the exact measurement.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt drives are built under the following required conditions: speeds of and power transmitted between drive and driven unit; suitable distance between shafts; and appropriate operating conditions.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Factors of power adjustment include speed ratio; shaft distance (long or short); type of drive unit (electric motor, internal combustion engine); service environment (oily, wet, dusty); driven unit loads (jerky, shock, reversed); and pulley-belt arrangement (open, crossed, turned).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] These are found in engineering handbooks and manufacturer's literature.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] When corrected, the power is compared to rated powers of the standard belt cross-sections at particular belt speeds to find a number of arrays that perform best.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] It is generally either large diameters or large cross-section that are chosen, since, as stated earlier, larger belts transmit this same power at low belt speeds as smaller belts do at high speeds.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] To keep the driving part at its smallest, minimal-diameter pulleys are desired.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Minimum pulley diameters are limited by the elongation of the belt's outer fibers as the belt wraps around the pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Small pulleys increase this elongation, greatly reducing belt life.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Minimal pulley diameters are often listed with each cross-section and speed, or listed separately by belt cross-section.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] After the cheapest diameters and belt section are chosen, the belt length is computed.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] If endless belts are used, the desired shaft spacing may need adjusting to accommodate standard-length belts.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] It is often more economical to use two or more juxtaposed V-belts, rather than one larger belt.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In large speed ratios or small central distances, the angle of contact between the belt and pulley may be less than 180°.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] If this is the case, the drive power must be further increased, according to manufacturer's tables, and the selection process repeated.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] This is because power capacities are based on the standard of a 180° contact angle.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Smaller contact angles mean less area for the belt to obtain traction, and thus the belt carries less power.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt drives depend on friction to operate, but excessive friction wastes energy and rapidly wears the belt.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Factors that affect belt friction include belt tension, contact angle, and the materials used to make the belt and pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Power transmission is a function of belt tension.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] However, also increasing with tension is stress (load) on the belt and bearings.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The ideal belt is that of the lowest tension that does not slip in high loads.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt tensions should also be adjusted to belt type, size, speed, and pulley diameters.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt tension is determined by measuring the force to deflect the belt a given distance per inch (or mm) of pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Timing belts need only adequate tension to keep the belt in contact with the pulley.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Fatigue, more so than abrasion, is the culprit for most belt problems.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] This wear is caused by stress from rolling around the pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] High belt tension; excessive slippage; adverse environmental conditions; and belt overloads caused by shock, vibration, or belt slapping all contribute to belt fatigue.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Vibration signatures are widely used for studying belt drive malfunctions.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Some of the common malfunctions or faults include the effects of belt tension, speed, sheave eccentricity and misalignment conditions.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The effect of sheave Eccentricity on vibration signatures of the belt drive is quite significant.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Although, vibration magnitude is not necessarily increased by this it will create strong amplitude modulation.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] When the top section of a belt is in resonance, the vibrations of the machine is increased.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] However, an increase in the machine vibration is not significant when only the bottom section of the belt is in resonance.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The vibration spectrum has the tendency to move to higher frequencies as the tension force of the belt is increased.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt slippage can be addressed in several ways.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt replacement is an obvious solution, and eventually the mandatory one (because no belt lasts forever).
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Often, though, before the replacement option is executed, retensioning (via pulley centerline adjustment) or dressing (with any of various coatings) may be successful to extend the belt's lifespan and postpone replacement.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Belt dressings are typically liquids that are poured, brushed, dripped, or sprayed onto the belt surface and allowed to spread around; they are meant to recondition the belt's driving surfaces and increase friction between the belt and the pulleys.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Some belt dressings are dark and sticky, resembling tar or syrup; some are thin and clear, resembling mineral spirits.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Some are sold to the public in aerosol cans at auto parts stores; others are sold in drums only to industrial users.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] To fully specify a belt, the material, length, and cross-section size and shape are required.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Timing belts, in addition, require that the size of the teeth be given.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] The length of the belt is the sum of the central length of the system on both sides, half the circumference of both pulleys, and the square of the sum (if crossed) or the difference (if open) of the radii.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] Thus, when dividing by the central distance, it can be visualized as the central distance times the height that gives the same squared value of the radius difference on, of course, both sides.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] When adding to the length of either side, the length of the belt increases, in a similar manner to the Pythagorean theorem.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] One important concept to remember is that as $D_{1}$ gets closer to $D_{2}$ there is less of a distance (and therefore less addition of length) as it approaches zero.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] On the other hand, in a crossed belt drive the *sum* rather than the difference of radii is the basis for computation for length.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] So the wider the small drive increases, the belt length is higher.
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] E.g. the pitch line for SPZ could be 8.5 mm from the bottom of the "V".
[src:ball-screw/belt-mechanical] In other words, 0–8.5 mm is 35° and 45° from 8.5 and above.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Two important concepts in gearing are **pitch surface** and **pitch angle**.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The pitch surface of a gear is the imaginary toothless surface given by averaging out the peaks and valleys of the individual teeth.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The pitch surface of an ordinary gear is the shape of a cylinder.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The pitch angle of a gear is the angle between the face of the pitch surface and the axis.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The most familiar kinds of bevel gears have pitch angles of less than 90 degrees and therefore are cone-shaped.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] This type of bevel gear is called **external** because the gear teeth point outward.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The pitch surfaces of meshed external bevel gears are coaxial with the gear shafts; the apexes of the two surfaces are at the point of intersection of the shaft axes.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The use of a genuine bevel gear has even greater importance for the reliability of the axle than any other spare part.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Bevel gears that have pitch angles of greater than ninety degrees have teeth that point inward and are called **internal** bevel gears.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Bevel gears that have pitch angles of exactly 90 degrees have teeth that point outward parallel with the axis and resemble the points on a crown, whence the name crown gear.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Mitre gears are useful for transmitting rotational motion at a 90-degree angle with a 1:1 ratio.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The cylindrical gear tooth profile corresponds to an involute (i.e. a triangle wave projected on the circumference of a circle), whereas the bevel gear tooth profile is an octoid (i.e. a triangle wave projected on the normal path of a circle of a sphere).
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] All traditional bevel gear generators (such as Gleason, Klingelnberg, Heidenreich & Harbeck, WMW Modul) manufacture bevel gears with an octoidal tooth profile.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] IMPORTANT: For 5-axis milled bevel gear sets it is important to choose the same calculation / layout like the conventional manufacturing method.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Simplified calculated bevel gears on the basis of an equivalent cylindrical gear in normal section with an involute tooth form show a deviant tooth form with reduced tooth strength by 10-28% without offset and 45% with offset [Diss.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Furthermore, those "involute bevel gear sets" cause more noise.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] There are two issues regarding tooth shape.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] One is the cross-sectional profile of the individual tooth.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The other is the line or curve on which the tooth is set on the face of the gear: in other words the line or curve along which the cross-sectional profile is projected to form the actual three-dimensional shape of the tooth.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The primary effect of both the cross-sectional profile and the tooth line or curve is on the smoothness of operation of the gears.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Some result in a smoother gear action than others.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The teeth on bevel gears can be straight, spiral or "zerol".
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] In **straight bevel gears**, the teeth are straight and parallel to the generators of the cone.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] This is the simplest form of bevel gear.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] It resembles a spur gear, only conical rather than cylindrical.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The gears in the floodgate picture are straight bevel gears.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] In straight bevel gear sets, when each tooth engages, it impacts the corresponding tooth and simply curving the gear teeth can solve the problem.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Spiral bevel gears have their teeth formed along spiral lines.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] They are somewhat analogous to cylindrical type helical gears in that the teeth are angled; however, with spiral gears, the teeth are also curved.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The advantage of the spiral tooth over the straight tooth is that they engage more gradually.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The contact between the teeth starts at one end of the gear and then spreads across the whole tooth.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] This results in a less abrupt transfer of force when a new pair of teeth come into play.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] With straight bevel gears, the abrupt tooth engagement causes more noise, especially at high speeds, and impact stress on the teeth which makes them unable to take heavy loads at high speeds without breaking.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] For these reasons, straight bevel gears are generally limited to use at linear speeds less than 1000 feet/min; or, for small gears, under 1000 rpm.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Zerol bevel gears are an intermediate type between straight and spiral bevel gears.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] Zerol bevel gears are designed with the intent of duplicating the characteristics of a straight bevel gear, but they are produced using a spiral bevel cutting process.
[src:ball-screw/bevel-gear] The bevel gear has many diverse applications such as locomotives, marine applications, automobiles, printing presses, cooling towers, power plants, steel plants, railway track inspection machines, etc.
